Use is new hook 



use() is a new hook that lets you use a Promise directly inside a component.

It automatically suspends until the promise resolves.

No need for: âŒ useEffect
âŒ useState
âŒ loading states manually


---

âœ… 1. Fetch Data Using use() (Simple Example)

import { use } from "react";

async function fetchUser() {
  const res = await fetch("https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/users/1");
  return res.json();
}

const userPromise = fetchUser();

export default function App() {
  const user = use(userPromise); // waits for promise to finish

  return (
    <div>
      <h2>{user.name}</h2>
      <p>{user.email}</p>
    </div>
  );
}

ğŸ” Description:

use(userPromise) pauses the component until data arrives.

When resolved â†’ component renders with the data.

No state/effect/loader needed.



---

âœ… 2. Using use() with async functions inside Component

import { use } from "react";

function getMessage() {
  return new Promise(resolve => {
    setTimeout(() => resolve("Hello from Future!"), 1000);
  });
}

export default function App() {
  const message = use(getMessage());

  return <h1>{message}</h1>;
}

ğŸ” Description:

React waits 1 second automatically.

Then shows "Hello from Future!".



---

âœ… 3. Using use() for passing async props

import { use } from "react";

export function Parent() {
  const data = new Promise(resolve => {
    resolve("Data from Parent");
  });

  return <Child info={data} />;
}

function Child({ info }) {
  const result = use(info);

  return <h2>{result}</h2>;
}

ğŸ” Description:

âœ” Parent gives a promise
âœ” Child uses use(info) to resolve it
âœ” Clean async flow